{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.1,0.05,0,0.86]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12441"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic infections can result in various patterns of tissue response and healing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a consequence of chronic inflammation in infectious diseases?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tissue architecture is always preserved despite inflammation","Inflammatory patterns are specific to individual pathogens","Regeneration of damaged cells consistently restores normal function","Acute neutrophilic infiltration resolves without tissue damage","Excessive scarring can be the primary cause of organ dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcessive scarring can be the primary cause of organ dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E. In many chronic infections, the exuberant scarring response becomes the major cause of organ dysfunction rather than direct damage from the pathogen itself. Examples include pipestem fibrosis of the liver in schistosomiasis, fibrosis of the bladder wall caused by schistosomal eggs, and constrictive fibrous pericarditis in tuberculosis. Chronic hepatitis B virus infection can lead to cirrhosis with dense fibrous septae surrounding nodules of regenerating hepatocytes, resulting in complete loss of normal liver architecture and altered blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute neutrophilic infiltration resolves without tissue damage\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can occur in mild acute inflammation, chronic infections typically lead to tissue damage and potential scarring.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETissue architecture is always preserved despite inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as chronic inflammation often leads to significant architectural distortion, as seen in liver cirrhosis where normal architecture is completely lost.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegeneration of damaged cells consistently restores normal function\u003C/strong\u003E - In chronic infections with extensive scarring, regeneration is often incomplete and abnormal, as seen in cirrhosis where regenerative nodules form but normal function is not restored.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory patterns are specific to individual pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E - While certain patterns may be suggestive of specific infections, the text notes that different types of host reactions often occur simultaneously, and similar patterns can be seen in responses to various agents, not just specific pathogens.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that patterns of tissue reaction in infectious processes rarely appear in pure form, as different types of host reactions often occur simultaneously. For example, the lung of an AIDS patient may show both cytolytic changes from cytomegalovirus infection and interstitial inflammation from \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic infections can lead to either complete healing or extensive scarring and fibrosis.","Excessive scarring from chronic inflammation can be the primary cause of organ dysfunction.","Schistosomiasis can cause pipestem fibrosis of the liver and fibrosis of the bladder wall.","Multiple patterns of tissue reaction often occur simultaneously in infectious processes."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 349."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:18:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13623"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"